        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>New Orleans, La.</placeName>
                <date>July 19<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1847</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd. I. Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dr Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Circumstances of an unavoidable<lb/> nature in my affairs having
                induced me to remove from <placeName>Columbia,<lb/> So. Ca.</placeName> Since the
                    <date>1st January</date> last, and now being permanently<lb/> located in this
                city, I am desirous of receiving the future<lb/> numbers of the “Occident” directed
                to me, “care <persName>Messrs.<lb/> E. I. Hart &amp; Co.</persName>
                <placeName>New Orleans, La.</placeName>”— you will please for-<lb/>-ward me No. 3 of
                fourth vol. For <date>June 1846</date>, and at the same<lb/> time inform me of my
                indebtedness to you, when <hi rend="underline">in the<lb/> course of next fall</hi>
                the amount shall be remitted or sub-<lb/>-ject to your order</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">In hopes my request will be attended to</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">I remain Resptfy yrs</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">
                <persName role="author">Emanuel Sampson</persName>
            </p>
            <p>P.S.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Permit me here to record a worthy act of <add>an</add> esteemed<lb/>
                Israelite, that should not pass unnoticed, but whose example might<lb/> well be
                followed by our wealthy brethren situated in places<lb/> as isolated, (as far as
                Judaism is concerned,) as the place where it<lb/> transpired, with honor to
                themselves, and the happy reflection<lb/> that they have been the humble instruments
                through which<lb/> T.O.</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p><hi rend="underline">another</hi> ordinance of the God of
                    <placeName>Israel</placeName> has been carried out,<lb/> I refer to <hi
                    rend="underline"><persName>Joseph J. Andrews, Esq.</persName> Of
                        <placeName>Memphis, Tenn</placeName></hi>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">A few months ago my family were on a visit<lb/> to
                    <placeName>Memphis</placeName>, where the Destroying Angel deprived me of<lb/>
                my first born, a promising Boy of 2 years old, when<lb/>
                <persName>Mr. Andrews</persName> called on the family (the writer being in this<lb/>
                city at the time) and very kindly informed them that<lb/> he had appropriated a
                tract of land for a <hi rend="underline">Jewish</hi><lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">Burial Ground</hi> for all Israelites who may hereafter<lb/>
                require the right of sepulchre in <placeName>Memphis</placeName>, (previous to<lb/>
                which time they had no separate ground); they declined ac-<lb/>-cepting of the
                generous offer, being desirous of removing<lb/> the remains of my child to this city
                for interment in<lb/> the Portuguese <add>Jewish</add> Burial Ground, where it now
                lies—Since<lb/> which time I am informed that the ground in
                    <placeName>Memphis</placeName> has<lb/> been neatly enclosed at the expense of
                    <persName>Mr. Andrews</persName>, and<lb/> the remains of a young German
                Israelite recently deceased,<lb/> interred therein—Had it been out of my power
                to<lb/> remove the corpse of my child, I should have had the<lb/> melancholy
                satisfaction of knowing that at least it was<lb/> deposited in ground sacred to
                Israelites.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Not having observed any notice on the subject in<lb/> the
                “Occident”, I have thought it a duty to suggest to you<lb/> the propriety of putting
                it in such a form that it may<lb/> have a beneficial effect</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">Very Respectfully</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">Yrs</p>
            <p rend="indent(11)">
                <persName role="author">E Sampson</persName>
            </p>
            <pb n="2V"/>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <hi rend="underline">Paid</hi>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">
                <placeName>No. 371 Walnut Street</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">
                <placeName>Penn.</placeName>
            </p>
